Agent-Inspection
Trigger: agent clicks "Accept" on property_review.php (existing action, agent_status → accepted). Everything below is new and sits between that moment and the existing approve/reject-listing decision. Accept status does not equal to approved(property be live)
    On accept, find-or-create the landlord-agent conversation for this property (reuse your start.php logic), context_type = 'agent_case'. Post a system_notice: "Agent [name] accepted this property — propose an inspection time below."
    Agent sends a new message type, inspection_schedule_request — a form-in-chat (same pattern as tenant_info_form) with one or more proposed date/time slots plus a free-text note.
    Landlord responds with inspection_schedule_response: picks a slot (or requests reschedule), selects an access method (landlord_present / lockbox_code / other, with a text field for the code/details), and ticks a consent statement — "I authorize [agent] to inspect [property] at [date/time] on my behalf." Submitting this writes the row described below.
    If the landlord requests reschedule instead of confirming: wipe the pending schedule row (same wipe-and-resend pattern you use for tenant info forms) and let the agent send a new inspection_schedule_request. No separate state machine needed — it's just resend.
    On confirm, system posts a system_notice to both sides: "Inspection confirmed: [date/time], access: [method]." This is the only place "trust" language shows up, and it's just the consent line from step 3 — no key, no separate prompt.
    Offline: the actual visit happens however the access method says (agent meets landlord, or uses the lockbox code, etc.) — nothing for the system to track here.
    Agent returns to property_review.php (or a new button there) and clicks "Mark inspection complete," setting completed_at on the inspection row.
    From there your existing approve/reject-listing logic takes over unchanged — agent_verified_at, agent_verified_by, property status transitions all stay as they are.

